WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:16.580
Great. Thank you so much. So the talk is in a way, in part, a continuation of what I showed very early in the morning, and that's the role of transcriptional variability in leukemia pathogenesis. These are my disclosures.

00:00:17.680 --> 00:00:37.560
And again, I don't want to belabor this point. I think there's ample evidence, there's really polyclonal evolution in MDS and AML pathogenesis. So in a preventative setting, we really have to think about all the clones that are there and not just the ones that emerge at any given time as dominant clones.

00:00:39.280 --> 00:00:47.280
And again, I've shown this slide in the morning. So we're, for that reason, very interested in all sorts of heterogeneity at the pre-leukemic stem cell level.

00:00:47.680 --> 00:00:58.160
Genetics, we've done for a long time, and I've shown you this morning that there's non-genetic mechanisms of stem cell heterogeneity, including transcriptional variability.

00:00:58.960 --> 00:01:16.980
In addition, I want to say for the targeting and preventative targeting, potentially, of pre-leukemic stem cells, we believe it's important to recognize that there may be really distinct biological principles in this evolution, the polyclonal evolution at early stages.

00:01:17.180 --> 00:01:17.660
